messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path
- /cms/admin/permission/remove

All HTTP methods acceptable?
- No

Acceptable methods (based on the code)
- HEAD: No
- POST: Yes
- OPTIONS: Yes
- TRACE: No
- GET: No
- PUT: No
- DELETE: No
- PATCH: No

Explanation
- The endpoint is declared in app/api/cms/admin.py as @admin_api.route("/permission/remove", methods=["POST"]).
- That blueprint (admin_api) is registered in app/api/cms/__init__.py with url_prefix="/admin".
- The cms blueprint created by create_cms() is registered in app/__init__.py with url_prefix="/cms".
- Combining the prefixes yields the full path /cms/admin/permission/remove.
- The route decorator explicitly lists methods=["POST"], so POST is accepted.
- Flask/Werkzeug automatically provides an OPTIONS handler for routes (unless explicitly disabled), so OPTIONS is accepted.
- Flask only auto-adds HEAD for routes that accept GET; since this route only accepts POST, HEAD is not added â€” therefore HEAD is not accepted.
- TRACE is not added by the route and is not auto-provided by Flask, so it's not accepted.
- GET, PUT, DELETE, PATCH are not listed in the route methods and thus are not accepted.
